`template/scripts/` is the CI/lint gate suite and CTX-tooling sync mechanism shipped into every scaffolded project — depending on it gets you `make check`-style static enforcement (unused deps, retired vocabulary, lint opt-in, function/file size, no bare `#[allow]`) plus the machinery to pull fresh `ctx-*` binaries and prompt files from the upstream CTX repo.

Two independent concerns share this directory and must not be conflated. First, the **check scripts** (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `retired_terms_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) are all invoked by ctx-verify and share a strict contract: enumerate files via `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` (never a filesystem walk, to avoid racing `target/` writers), emit failures as `FAIL: <path>:<line>: ...` lines (grep's `-H` + `/dev/null` trick is the common idiom for guaranteeing the `path:line:` prefix even on a single match), and exit 1 if any FAIL was emitted. ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser depends on this exact format across all of them — changing one script's output shape without checking the parser breaks verification silently.

Second, the **sync/generation scripts** form a pipeline: `install-tools.sh` builds and copies `ctx-*` binaries from an external CTX repo (default `../CTX`) into `target/debug/`; `update-template.sh` is the umbrella entry point that re-syncs `install-tools.sh` itself, invokes it, mirrors a hardcoded list of check scripts/configs/prompts, then splices tool-contracts into `CLAUDE.md`; `gen_tool_contracts.sh` and `gen_readme_architecture.sh` both do marker-delimited splice/replace into docs (`CLAUDE.md` and `README.md` respectively), sharing the `--write`/`--check` mode convention and `FAIL:`-line reporting in check mode. Marker strings in `gen_tool_contracts.sh` and `update-template.sh` must stay byte-identical or the splice breaks silently. `update-template.sh`'s mirror lists (`TOP_LEVEL_FILES`, `CHECK_SCRIPTS`, `PROMPTS`) are the single point that must be updated when adding a new check script here — otherwise it won't propagate to scaffolded projects.

`cycle_check.sh` is explicitly a stub (real work deferred to a dylint rule); `rationale_check.py` is also called an MVP placeholder pending a dylint rule. Both are intentionally incomplete, not broken.